posts.com:
We have all heard of TJPW prospects bolting for Stardom in search of greater success: Mina Shirakawa and Unagi Sayaka have been Artist and Future champions; Poi has been Artist and High-Speed champion; and Mirai has won the Cinderella.

But what if I tell you that there is one particular member of the Stardom roster who will benefit the most from going the other way around?

That would be Waka Tsukiyama, the promotion's resident punching bag.

Ever since she began wrestling in September 2020, Waka has won exactly one match: a tag match in January 2021. In Stardom? Her best result has been a draw. Every other time, she gets pinned or submitted.

Now some will say, "Be patient! She will eventually get a push! See Lady C." But the way I see it, I think she does not mesh well in Stardom's mostly grim and foreboding atmosphere. Lady C is tall, which is rare among joshi, and that explains why she received a mini-push last year. What does Waka have, besides being born in America and knowing how to speak English (which Mina Shirakawa can also do, but better)?

TJPW, on the other hand, presents a much more relaxed and colorful environment that would fit Waka perfectly. You do not need to be the best wrestler in the world to connect with the fans (though it certainly helps); you just have to be fun to watch and engage with. And it shows in the characters. Miyu Yamashita is the no-nonsense Stardom-style martial artist; Yuka Sakazaki is a majo; Maki Itoh is a vulgar ex-idol; Suzume is a wrestling bee, Shoko Nakajima is a wolf warrior, Miu Watanabe is a boisterous big girl, and so forth.

All of them captivate the audience in one way or another. Waka already has the look, so if she can find her inner voice and turn it into a captivating character, she will garner more success in TJPW than she has ever had in Stardom.

posts.com:
So this is comparing WCW numbers from July 1999 to July 2000. Average attendance is down 55%. Average gate down 53%. Monday night ratings are down 25% (although Dave points out that it's not a fair comparison because Nitro switched from 3 hours to 2. So if you account for that, it's even worse and would actually be about a 31% drop). PPV buyrates down 45%. In July 99, they sold out around 17% of their house shows. In July 2000, they sold out exactly 0% of them. A lot can change in a year. And while I'm pointing it out, it's worth noting that Vince Russo was in charge for probably 75% of that year.

Dave Lagana writes in, talking his experience working on "Friends" and talking about how most TV shows are written by writing teams and how stories are crafted in TV writing rooms and so on and so forth. Basically, it leads to the one big question every writer, booker, and performer should ask themselves: how will the audience react to the long-term story? Not how loud the momentary pop is or how much you were able to swerve the audience with a surprise that doesn't make any sense, etc. The point he's trying to make is that Vince Russo is doing literally everything wrong and he has no idea how to write television. He's also pretty fed up with Russo's constant everything-is-a-shoot booking, where they openly acknowledge scripts and bookers and shit in every segment. He's not the only one.

In regards to Russo blaming his failures on Turner's standards & practices department, Bischoff called it "a crock that Russo peddled" and said his excuses were "a load of crap."

We have all heard of TJPW prospects bolting for Stardom in search of greater success: Mina Shirakawa and Unagi Sayaka have been Artist and Future champions; Poi has been Artist and High-Speed champion; and Mirai has won the Cinderella.

But what if I tell you that there is one particular member of the Stardom roster who will benefit the most from going the other way around?

That would be Waka Tsukiyama, the promotion's resident punching bag.

Ever since she began wrestling in September 2020, Waka has won exactly one match: a tag match in January 2021. In Stardom? Her best result has been a draw. Every other time, she gets pinned or submitted.

Now some will say, "Be patient! She will eventually get a push! See Lady C." But the way I see it, I think she does not mesh well in Stardom's mostly grim and foreboding atmosphere. Lady C is tall, which is rare among joshi, and that explains why she received a mini-push last year. What does Waka have, besides being born in America and knowing how to speak English (which Mina Shirakawa can also do, but better)?

TJPW, on the other hand, presents a much more relaxed and colorful environment that would fit Waka perfectly. You do not need to be the best wrestler in the world to connect with the fans (though it certainly helps); you just have to be fun to watch and engage with. And it shows in the characters. Miyu Yamashita is the no-nonsense Stardom-style martial artist; Yuka Sakazaki is a majo; Maki Itoh is a vulgar ex-idol; Suzume is a wrestling bee; Shoko Nakajima is a wolf warrior, Miu Watanabe is a boisterous big girl, and so forth.

All of them captivate the audience in one way or another. Waka already has the look, so if she can find her inner voice and turn it into a captivating character, she will garner more success in TJPW than she has ever had in Stardom.
